## TypeScript Rules

- Strict mode is enabled — no `any`, ever. Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
- All exported functions must have explicit return types.
- Use `satisfies` for type assertions instead of `as`.
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes.
- `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` is on — always check array/object access results.
- ESM only: use `.js` extensions in all relative imports (even for `.ts` files).

## Code Style

- Biome is the formatter and linter — do not suggest ESLint/Prettier changes.
- Max function length: 50 lines. Decompose if longer.
- Max file length: 500 lines. Split into modules if longer.
- `camelCase` variables/functions, `PascalCase` types/classes, `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` constants.
- Group imports: built-ins → external packages → internal → types.
- No default exports except for Next.js pages/layouts and React components (use named exports elsewhere).

{{#if (eq template "nextjs")}}
## Next.js Rules

- App Router only — never suggest Pages Router patterns.
- Default to Server Components; add `"use client"` only for event handlers, hooks, and browser APIs.
- Use Server Actions for all data mutations.
- Use `next/image` for images, `next/font` for fonts.
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix only for env vars that must be readable by the browser.
- Keep route handlers in `app/api/*/route.ts`.
{{/if}}

{{#if (eq template "api")}}
## API Rules

- Routes in `src/routes/`, services in `src/services/` — business logic belongs in services.
- Validate ALL inputs at the route boundary using Zod schemas from `src/schemas/`.
- Always return `{ data, error, meta }` shaped JSON.
- Never expose stack traces to clients in production.
- Use correct HTTP semantics: 201 for creation, 204 for no-body success, 422 for validation errors.
{{/if}}

{{#if (eq template "cli")}}
## CLI Rules

- One command per file under `src/commands/`.
- Every option needs a description for `--help` output.
- Exit with code 0 (success), 1 (error), or 2 (misuse).
- Write diagnostics to `stderr`, machine-readable output to `stdout`.
{{/if}}

{{#if (eq template "react")}}
## React Rules

- Feature-based structure: `src/features/<feature>/`.
- No direct fetching in components — use hooks from `src/api/` with TanStack Query.
- Routes in `src/router.tsx` using `createBrowserRouter`.
- Global state in Zustand stores (`src/store/`).
- One custom hook per file in `src/hooks/`.
{{/if}}

{{#if (neq database "none")}}
## Database Rules

- Schema lives in `prisma/schema.prisma` — edit there, then migrate.
- Always run `{{#if (eq packageManager "npm")}}npm run db:migrate{{/if}}{{#if (eq packageManager "pnpm")}}pnpm db:migrate{{/if}}{{#if (eq packageManager "yarn")}}yarn db:migrate{{/if}}{{#if (eq packageManager "bun")}}bun run db:migrate{{/if}}` after schema changes.
- No raw SQL unless Prisma cannot express the query.
- Never call Prisma client directly in route handlers — go through the service layer.
{{/if}}

## Testing

- Test files mirror `src/` structure under `tests/`.
- Unit test every service function and utility.
- Integration tests for all API routes / commands.
- Do not mock what you can use in-process (prefer real implementations with test fixtures).

## What to Avoid

- Speculative features — only build what's explicitly requested.
- `@ts-ignore` or `@ts-expect-error` without a comment explaining why.
- Installing new dependencies without first checking existing ones.
- Committing `.env` files — always use `.env.example` as the template.
- Inline TODO comments — open an issue instead.
